column22: As a first generation-college student, I don't have anyone in my immediate family to reach out to in regards to applying to professional schools. I had to take it upon myself to look for resources to help with the college process. Applying to medical school is a whole different situation. While I do have resources at my college, I feel like it's more comforting to be able to meet with someone individually. At Hunter, a majority of the STEM majors are actively pursuing medical school. So there's only so much our pre-health advisors can do for us. It's just better to have an individualized experience because they're able to address your personal issues over general issues of the student body. Everyone's path to medical school is different. Being able to hear someone's story will help me pinpoint where to start. Also having someone's feedback on what you were already doing (summer research, clinical research) is helpful.
column23: I guess it's the aspect of being able to speak with someone who was once in your position. While you may not have experienced similar hardships or be under the same circumstances, what we have in common is the pursuit of medical school during our undergraduate years. Just being able to hear how someone got to where they are is helpful because you get a sense of what to look out for and reflect about yourself and how you're going about it. You're no longer dealing with the process alone because someone will be there to give you guidance.
column24: Well I'll list a few. On the last week of lent, my mom makes this traditional, Ecuadorian soup called Fanesca. How I used to describe it as a kid is "fish soup". The type of music that we dance to at parties can be described as a range of merengue, cumbia and traditional Ecuadorian music. I was exposed to Ecuadorian culture the most when I visited my family there. I was exposed to their traditional dishes (guinea pig) as well the dances they perform in celebration of a saint.
column25: Before you sit down at a family gathering, you must greet everyone. Do not leave without saying goodbye to everyone, especially your elders. For celebrations, while there is a set time, it is expected that a majority of those invited arrive around 1-2 hours later. It takes a while for the party to begin. My family isn't too strict with regards to formal and informal language as long as we are respectful. When I visited Ecuador, it was expected for me to behave my best as the impression I leave on others would affect the image of my family.

column24: Some observable and concrete elements of my Jamaican culture include a strong emphasis on family and respect, caribbean dishes, reggae and dancehall music. Holidays are spent with lively family gatherings full of laughter and reminiscing.
column25: The emphasis placed on great character in my culture speaks volumes in everyday social interactions. Tardiness is considered disrespectful, respect shown to elders is critical and manners are essential. From youth, children are taught to greet everyone they come into contact with appropriately and to represent their family and upbringing in every setting. Friendship is taught to be more about the quality of they people you keep close rather than the number of friends you have. These unspoken rules make it easy for me to identify someone from a culture similar to my own.

column24: My most memorable and favorite parts of my Ecuadorian culture are the food. For certain holidays we have various traditions. For example, for our day of the dead, we make a drink called "Colada Morada" and bread called "Guaguas de Pan". We typically celebrate it at the beginning of November and the drink symbolizes the deceased's blood and bread represent their body to put it in the simplest way. It is a bit similar to a religious viewpoint. It always feels cozy and the process of making it is very long but very rewarding. Our family usually comes together and we are grateful to have each other. I love that food can bring us together and it is also something that everyone enjoys. When I went to Ecuador in past years, I often bonded most with my family through food events and discussions.
column25: Some major things that I have grown up with have typically always been related with manners. My mom would always notice manners in any of friends or partners that I'd introduce and that would be the only lasting impression she would have for the rest of their encounters. Our greetings for example are typically always warm with a kiss on the cheek, hug and the host always attending the guest. The guest would naturally have to continue conversations and the host would be in charge of handling that the guests were not bored. I remember that I would always ask if the guest's would like water but my mom and aunts would say, "Andrea you don't ask, you just give". This showed me that one must always take an initiative in everything one does as well as be kind and mindful of others and their perspectives/ feelings.

column22: The application and matriculation to medical school is a difficult and intricate process. I want to be a successful applicant. PrIMES goals in setting a curriculum and benchmarks with a mentor provide the guidance I seek on my path to medical school. Likewise, the pairing with a minority student who understands the process is a great resource to a prospective medical student like myself. I understand that PrIMES will set me up for success.
column23: With both a curriculum and set benchmarks, the PrIMES program seems to push students towards progress and better preparation for the medical school application and med school in general. The mentor seems like it would be a great resource for both questions and guidance. I also understand that the program will teach me skills important for my education further on. Therefore, I understand that I will be taught skills useful to me as I persure more education.
column24: I am Venezuelan. Venezuela has a plethora of amazing foods including arepas, tequeños, cachapas, and more. Most of the dishes are corn-based and recipes are shared with neighboring countries. Religious holidays are national holidays in Venezuela. The country is mostly Roman Catholic with other Christian denominations following as the second most practiced religion. Each province has their saint or a specific holiday. Venezuelan music and art are highly influenced by Carribean themes. Gaitas Zulianas, a style of music from my province that falls under folk focuses on romantic and political stories. Common instruments are the cuatro, maracas, and tambora.
column25: A big part of Venezuelan culture revolves around family and religion. There, the concept of leaving home at 18 is more strange than staying home throughout college (unlike the US). The family also tends to live relatively close to one another.  The extended family is not a separated from the nuclear family or closer relatives. Close friends are also considered family and even introduced to children as such.  As mentioned previously, religion ties very closely to culture. Children, as well as adults, ask for a blessing from their elders in greetings and goodbyes. Nonetheless, it is customary that you greet/say goodbye to everyone with a bendición. The respect towards elders is also seen in the language as in Spanish, one can use more respectful words or conjugations to denote feelings of respect towards someone. The elderly usually represent wisdom and are very respected. When making big decisions, their opinions are always valued and considered. WAe protect our elderly and take care of them in our homes (when they need assistance). Eye contact is expected and is almost considered a form of communication.

column22: I grew up in a not so good neighborhood in Brooklyn where my education wasn't the best foundation. The first time I attended college (straight out of high school), I felt unprepared, like if I hadn't received the same education as my peers. This time around, I feel more wise and have taught myself how to take advantage of my sources and study hard, but a part of me still feels lost/feels like I am not good enough compared to others who had a stronger educational background. Because of this fear, I try to work hard and try to once again, take advantage of all opportunities. Ideally, I want to go to a medical school in New York City / Long Island and I would appreciate any guidance, especially from someone who may have experienced some of the same set backs as myself.
column23: PriMES will help me become a successful applicant because as a mentee I will be partnered with someone who has already gone through the process. I can do everything by the book on my own, but having someone to help guide me to success and who has experience is more beneficial.
column24: I am American Puerto Rican (spanish was not taught to me as a child), but we do have some very distinct cultural traditions. For instance, Christmas-Eve is a big holiday in my family. We always have a big party at my moms house, all my siblings, cousins, aunts and uncles come over. My mom usually makes pernil (pork shoulder), arroz con gondules (rice and chick peas) and of course pasteles. My mom is usually playing La India or some sort of Salsa and we eat, listen to music, and enjoy each others company. We also have a big tradition in my family of getting together on the weekend at my Titi Jenny's house (she is the head of the family) and playing Loteria (bingo). Titi Jenny always cooks like if it were Thanksgiving and the guys are usually watching some sort of sporting game, fight, or playing dominos. No matter what time of day it is, there is always freshly brewed bustelo (coffee) and sliced block cheese.
column25: One major unspoken rule in my culture is you always give everyone a hello kiss on the cheek when you enter a room, even if you do not know them.

column22: It is my dream and my passion to be a doctor and I feel that as a black woman in medicine, I am not represented as much as I should be. I want to be the change that we need in the workforce. Not that there needs to be less of any other race or gender, but it would be nice to see more people like me. I want to help other people and contribute to the community and with this program, I will be able to contribute to underdeveloped and often overlooked communities. It would be a great honor to participate in PrIMES.

column24: This is not saying that this is an element of all black culture, but being an African American woman, I tend to rock many diverse hair styles including braids, twists, afros, and much more. I am also half Dominican, so I listen to a bit of hispanic music and sometimes eat traditional hispanic food in my house.
column25: My parents always taught me to respect my elders and say hello to everyone who lives in my building. I see a lot of these people everyday and it is respectful to make some sort of conversation and not act like they are strangers. On buses and trains, I give my seat to the elderly or pregnant women/ women with babies. I look everyone in their eyes when they are talking to me (sometimes I get a bit anxious and find it awkward to look at someone in their eyes for too long but I will always make eye contact). I treat people the way I want to be treated so I tend to hold doors for people, say thank you when someone does something considerate for me, I help people with strollers carry them up or down the stairs in the train station and much more. Overall, my parents just taught me to be a courteous person and to be the person people think positively about.

column22: As an African American woman I am striving to become a surgeon in an America that makes it very difficult for me to reach this goal. Nonetheless, from experience I know that anything worth doing is never easy, and I have sought out the "PRIMES" program because I think that the form of mentorship available to me will help me reach my goals of medical school specifically because the plan will be geared to me and not everyone else. Another reason I yearn to participate in this program is to maximize my potential.  I am a French major (my native language) and I am using my electives to take my science classes. I love speaking french because I love connecting with new individuals, and science has always intrigued me but I would love for someone to see my vision and help me maximize my interests and strengths in my application for medical school.
column23: Personally, I am a planner. For me, even when I have a tentative plan it keeps me motivated and less stressed. This is not to say that I am stressed and worried, but I would really like to utilize my prime mentor to help map out a plan that works for me while taking into account my major and future medical goals in combination with someone who has already gone through the application process.
column24: I am half African American, and half Haitian. As a family we celebrate Kwanzaa,Haitian independence day. As a granddaughter of Haitian immigrants family is a big part of our culture and many of the celebrations often involve the entire family. I would say that this is an important concept that comes from both these cultures: family dynamic.
column25: Growing up I was always raised to respect my elders which meant to address them by "Mr/Dr and Mrs/Ms/Dr". I was taught to engage in this way because it is respectful and I would do nothing less. In terms of nature of friendship I have always been taught that friends are meant to be supportive not competitive or negative. As a child, I have always been taught to make eye contact with everyone from everyday conversations to professional interviews, and amongst friends (for respect). In terms of concepts of time I have always been taught to be early to things because punctuality is also a form of respect (on both sides: respecting my times and the time of others).

column24: Food and music are very important parts of my culture, and in turn very important to me. It goes outside of the surface level satisfaction of enjoying good food and dancing to good music, these aspects of my culture allow us to bask in a shared experience: being Afro-Latina, being Dominican. For a long time I felt safe being racially ambiguous or mistaken as biracial because of the privilege associated with being part white, as I learned to accept myself and my culture the concrete elements of my culture became that much more important to me. I don't mind people hearing Bad Bunny blaring through my headphones on my way to class and I openly invite friends and peers to enjoy traditional dishes like locreo and sancocho.
column25: A fundamental pillar of my culture is to be very serving to the people that we care about, specifically friends. The nature of friendship is very unique in Dominican culture. I was always taught to treat friends as if they were family. From paying for friend's food at my birthday dinners or cooking them home cooked meals. Selflessness is a high admired trait in my culture. We are always expected to show the value of our relationships through acts of service.

column24: The cultural group with which I am associated are the Dominicans. column24: I am originally from Cameroon (West Africa). My people wear very colorful clothing (ankara) to exhibit our culture. Some of our staple foods are platian, rice and fufu. In most remote areas of the country, people use instruments like drums, jingles calabashes and tambourines to produce beautiful sounds of music.
column25: Respect is an important part of social interaction in my culture, especially when it come to interaction with elders. Some unspoken rules are, holding your right wrist with your left hand when greetting (shaking hands ) with an elderly person, making eye contact with elderly people is frowned upon, friendships between people of opposite sex is very uncommon.

column22: I am interested in participating in PrIMES because I have been eager to become an Obstetrician Gynecologist since eight years old. I admire every one in the medical profession and I have an unwavering commitment to achieve my goal of becoming a doctor. But as I envision myself as an Ob/Gyn, I  also imagine the intense and rigorous journey ahead of me. Thus, I would like to join PrIMES as I am in need of the knowledge and opportunities that will aid me in successfully reaching my career goal. As a mentor myself, I recognize the great impact that a mentee/mentor relationship can have on both individuals and I yearn to develop a close relationship with my mentor in this program.
column23: Overall, I imagine that this program will allow me to gain a lot more exposure into the medical school application process than I have now. I hope to obtain information about the most useful books, tools, and websites that will help me ace my MCATS. I am also curious to know what makes a medical school personal statement compelling to an admissions committee. Additionally, I hope to have access to pre-health job, volunteer, and networking opportunities through this program. I believe PrIMES will benefit me because I’ll be surrounded by individuals who have experienced the same process and can offer me a first-hand account on the dos and dont’s of applying to medical school.
column24: As an American with an Aruban mother and Haitian father, I view myself under multiple identities. Along with pop, R&B, and rap, I thoroughly enjoy dancing to Kompa, Reggae, and Calypso music. In fact, I love to dance and I often teach others how to dance Kompa. Although, I mainly celebrate American holidays, I have traveled to Aruba and other parts of the Caribbean to partake in Carnival. Likewise, I am also a Christian and am devoted to my faith. Therefore, I regularly attend church services and I celebrate the Christmas holiday.
column25: In both my mother and father’s household, it is imperative that I greet every person with a hug/kiss on the cheek. This represents a sign of respect and love to everyone in the room. I have also celebrated holidays where the family is segregated by the “grown folks table” and the “kid’s table” and at nineteen, I am still not able to hang around “grown folk’ business.” In addition, although I have different relationships with my parents, I am not allowed to talk back, curse, or raise my voice to either. However,  my mother and I have more of a friendship than my father and I. I would say that my family members value respect above all else in my culture.

column24: I am Ecuadorian and a big celebration we have is on New Year's Eve, where we celebrate "año viejo". The celebration consists of large gatherings of family, friends, and community members to say goodbye to the year. The night is filled with parodies of plays, karaoke, "burning of Año Viejo" (in Ecuador), joke, and the 12 grapes once the clock strikes midnight. That's my favorite celebration. My favorite dish is called guata (Ecuadorian tripe stew). It's made out of a peanut sauce, potatoes, and tripe. My mom only makes it a few times a year and each time is more delicious than the last.
column25: In Ecuadorian culture (as well as a lot of other Latin countries), you must always respect your elders. Generally in the stereotypical family the order of those served food first go as: children, elders, guests, rest of the family, and the person/people who cooked.

column22: - The PriMES program is an outstanding opportunity for me to grow and reflect upon my strong interest in pursuing a doctorate degree and expand upon my passion for public health. As a minority-based student, I find it hard to find such resources that educate students in my community. I look forward to forming a bond with my mentor and I am extremely passionate to be guided by their advice about the medical professions. I would love to express my interests in medical and public health with my potential mentor and seek their guidance along the way. I also aspire to meet and interact with other underrepresented students with strong interests in medicine like myself.
column23: The journey to becoming a doctor can be challenging and stressful but I truly believe that  it is worth every second of saving lives and ensuring the wellness of the community around me. The PrIMES program will educate and advice me further of the medical school process. I am currently in my 3rd year and I would really like support and advice about the MCAT, personal statement, volunteer service, and medical school application tips. The PriMES program will be an amazing support system for me and will genuinely help me through my journey as a pre-medical student.
column24: I come from an ethnically diverse background that consists of Guyanese/Indian/Afro-Caribbean descent. While I am still learning more about the origins of my Guyanese background, much of my culture is circumnavigated by Caribbean and Indian traditions (food, lifestyle, religious attire, etc) because my home country (Guyana) is located in South America. I practice the Hindu religion but am open-minded about other faith systems. The Guyanese culture is widely open-minded about different cultural influences and its music like religious Sanskrit (Hindu religious songs), Hindi, and reggae. The food that I eat is  inspired by vegetarian Indian/African/British cuisine and its varieties are endless. Some examples are flatbread (roti), curried vegetables, and lentils. I practice religious Hindu holidays, like Diwali and Navratri, and my family also celebrate Christian holidays, like Christmas. My cultural diversity defines who I am and I take much pride in it. I also love to meet people of different backgrounds to learn more about their cultural influences as well!
column25: In my culture, respect is the most important unspoken rule in everyday social interactions. I was raised to always respect others opinions, beliefs, and theories. Each individual has their own perception of the world and I was expected to respect that concept. The elderly are to be treated with the uttermost respect and compassion because they are believed to be the most wise and knowledgable. I was also raised to form relationships with people who would have a positive impact on me for the sake of my mental wellness. Finally, the concept of time is widely emphasized. Time is an ongoing process — it does not wait for anyone or anything — and as such, I must make the most of it and try to do the most good that I can within that time frame. These cultural rules have positively-shaped me into the person that I am today.

column25: Everyone deserves respect. This is something was was instilled into me as a child and is a rule that I live by. Being Consdierate is an integral, if not, the most important part of who I am. I treat everyone with kindness because the world already has so much negativity. I love extremely hard, but not to an unhealthy point. It just means I hold all my friends and relatives in high regard and would do everything in my power to ensure they are alright and that everyone feels as if they are safe around me. Eye contact is important to me as well. It's an indicator of full attention although I do understand, even for me, it can be intimidating to look at someone directly for a sustained period of time, I do think it was one of the more rather obvious indicators that you have someones attention. Respecting people older than me is a given and always has been, and I strive to make sure expectations are met and maintained. column24: A huge aspect of my culture is my religion. We have to major holidays, Eid, in which we wear our best clothes. column24: Some observable and concrete elements of my culture - the Dominican culture - include that of the Spanish language and Roman Catholic religion. Others are that of merengue and bachata music, cuisines ranging from “mangu” or mashed plantains and “sancocho” or soup composed with a variety of meats and tubers, and holidays like the “carnaval” or carnival that are held annually to celebrate our gained independence from our  neighboring country, Haiti.
column25: Some unspoken rules around everyday social interactions in my culture include that of “besando la mano” or “kissing the hand” of my superior family members, whether that be parents and grandparents, whenever I encounter them. This does not mean that I physically kiss their hands, but is rather a form of asking for their blessing; it is through this action that I demonstrate my respect for them. Furthermore, another unspoken rule around everyday social interactions in my culture is that of being hospitable whenever family or friends are invited to my home - I must offer them any comforts that come to mind and thus treat them the way I would like to be treated if the scenario were different.

column24: I have visited my parents' home country, Nigeria, many times in the past, and my favorite part to this day has always been the food. Traditional Nigerian dishes range from spicy to even spicier, and I love it. One of my favorites is suya, which is tiny pieces of beef covered in "suya spice," which has fire in it that comes straight from the sun. When it comes to traditional dress, Nigerians waste no amount of color or style. Even the men dress as fabulously as the women do; they wear something called agbada and a hat while the women wear gele with their traditional dresses. These are usually worn at big events or parties, which can last up to twelve hours (I've been to a party in Nigeria that literally lasted twelve hours). At these parties, the music is playing so loudly that you feel the beat in your chest. Although to make up for it, artists like Davido, Wizkid, and Burna Boy make their music impossible not to dance to.
column25: In Nigerian culture, children are expected to respect their elders and offer to do any housework in their place. For example, it's rude to let an elder or a guest clean up after you. When we were growing up, our parents didn't let us go to a friend's house if they didn't know the friend's parents, and they certainly never let us sleep over at a friend's house no matter how familiar. My parents don't like it when we don't make eye contact while they're talking to us. Also, in Nigeria, I suspect that time is not as strictly adhered to as it is in this country because Nigerian are always late to everything. We have a joke in my family that if a party is scheduled to start at 4pm, then we can plan for the Nigerian guests to arrive at 8pm.

column23: I think PrRIMES will help me become more organized as an applicant. Being able to speak to medical students and to be mentored by them is very helpful because they can help me better realize my strengths and weaknesses, and how to use them to improve as an applicant. I can learn about the application process and what’s needed to be a competitive applicant on my own, but to have someone who was in my situation give me advice on how to improve as an applicant is priceless. They can help me improve in areas I may not know how to improve in, or in areas I may not have noticed that needs improvement. I do not have any friends or family who know about applying to medical school, so being able to have a mentor who understands the process is important; they can share information and resources I may not have known about on my own.
column24: My family is from the Dominican Republic, so I eat rice and beans for dinner almost every day (which is a cool and funny experience to think about). My favorite kind of rice and beans is rice with green pigeon peas, which are called gandules. As Dominicans we also enjoy our plátanos (plantains), and in my family we eat them at least once a week (usually a few times a week). My family has a Thanksgiving dinner, even though my mother was not born in America. We celebrate Christmas and it’s my favorite holiday, as well as my mother’s favorite holiday. My mom likes to listen to modern American and Latin music,  but she also loves to listen to her favorite Hispanic songs from the 70’s and 80’s when she was growing up. I sometimes listen to those songs on my own time because they can be very calming and pleasing to the ears. I personally love listening to reggaetón, but I do occasionally listen to bachata.
column25: When someone arrives home, we always greet each other. Whenever someone is leaving the house, we let each other know where we are going. My brothers and I text our mom to let her know where we are. If I am going somewhere, such as school, I text my mom when I am on the train, when I arrive to class, and when I’m on my way home. My mom and I have an unspoken rule that I can’t stay out too late, so if I stay out past 8 or 9 pm, my mother gets really worried (unless I am with her). Whenever my family talks to each other, we make eye contact. My mom has created a safe and fun environment for us where my brothers and I can be friends with our mom, and my mom emphasizes to me that she wants me to regard her as my best friend, which I do. My brothers and mom give each other space, but we try to make jokes and be happy together.

column24: I am African-American and I wouldn't say we have many elements of our culture, at least in my family. My family loves a variety of music since I live with my grandma who comes from the 50s/60s, my aunt who's from the 70s/80s and my sibling who loves rap from this day and age. We don't celebrate holidays as a part of our religious observance, but it's kind of known that my family goes all-out when it comes to Thanksgiving. We love to come together for those few days, make a ton of food and watch the parade on TV. My family just really values togetherness and sticking up for each other.

column24: My parents are from Dominican Republic. I was raised listening to bachata, merengue, and romantic music. I was also lucky enough to get home cooked meals. I eat mangu, Sancocho, avocado, rice, beans, chicken, fish, quipe, flan and much more. As well as many other cultures, we celebrate Independence Day, Duarte Day,  carnival, Día de Altagracia, Christmas and have many more different holidays. Baseball is one of our favorite sports. If you’re not a Boston fan, your not Dominica (this is a just a view, not reliable). Apart from your mother and father, almost all Dominicans I know have a padrino y madrina(godfather and godmother). My padrinos are like another set of parents. They’re always there when they’re needed. Those in my culture enjoy music and their food.
column25: Most rules are about respect and duty. When it comes to elders and older family members, you should always address them formally. Words like tu is not acceptable. We must address our elders with usted. There are roles each family member has. As the “woman of the house”, your responsibilities include but are not limited to cleaning home, cooking, taking care of children, and making sure you are always home at a reasonable hour. As a woman visiting other homes, you always offer help. This is a way to show respect.  Other than responsibilities and how to greet your elders, there are other unspoken rules. For example, before you go to sleep and when you wake up you say good morning and “la bendición mami y la bendición papi”. As a response you would usually get “dios te bendiga”.  When we do this, we are asking for a blessing and are told “may god bless you”. There are also other customs. It’s customary to say “duen provecho”. This is a way to say enjoy your meal. When it comes to morning, Dominicans morn differently to customs in the United States. Everyone shows up to the funeral because it’s whats required and instead of wearing all black clothing we wear all white and over time many may start to wear clothing with mute colors. There are other unspoken rules in my culture, but this is all I can think about at this moment.

column24: I am a blend of two different worlds that overlap in the most beautiful of ways. In my culture we are generous and pious. We are people who begin our day thankful that we woke up. Every meal is flavorful and leaves you so full you cant help, but laugh as grandma scoops another spoon of rice onto your plate. Our culture is to love your peers as you love yourself. We are the people who smile at strangers, who make meals for the poor, who bring you a cup of tea after you’ve declined it. We are the people who fight each other over who gets to pay the bill. Our music is loud and heartfelt. Our songs cast the memories of fresh fruit and  the green land of the country side. Our songs tell the younger generations what it would be like if they could visit. Our clothes are modest, but embroidered by hand so that the fine details are the main part of the dress.
column25: A big unspoken rule is how you speak to your parents; even when your parents upset you, you don’t raise your voice higher than theirs. Friendships are believed to have a huge impact on the person you become, so the people you surround yourself with should be people who are reflective of you, or who make you better. We never leave an event on time. As you are leaving expect their to be seven new conversations before you have taken another step and said bye.

column24: I moved to New York from the Philippines 7 years ago, so I still completely consider myself as a Filipino citizen despite the fact that I received my US citizenship 6 years ago. I hold my Filipino culture dearly because of the food. There is a gathering we call a Boodle Fight where big banana leaves are laid out on multiple tables filled with rice, grilled seafood, pork, chicken, etc. During a Boodle Fight, family and friends come together and eat everything on the banana leaf with their bare hands. It is special because it is a moment I've had filled with laughter, good food and the company of amazing family. I think the best part about the Boodle Fight is that it can be celebrated any time. No holidays, just the need to come together as a family and that's what defines the Filipino culture.
column25: In the Filipino culture, we have an unspoken rule on greeting the elders as a sign of respect. Instead of hugs and kisses, we have to "bless". This means that the elderly will put their hand out for you to reach and put on your forehead and say "bless". Another unspoken rule is about skin color. Filipinos are stuck to the mentality of keeping their skin as light as possible. Despite the powerful heat, individuals will wear layers of sweaters with jeans in order to hide their skin from the sun. I grew up with this idea that being light meant being better. That mentality changed when I moved to New York and opened up to the American culture of being tan is the way to go. However, there is an unspoken view of light skin supremacy across the world. This is where the Filipino and American culture cross paths. The racism in American influenced the views Filipinos have on skin color. That is an unspoken rule that I wish didn't exist in my everyday social interaction with Filipinos and Americans.

column22: I would like to participate in PrIMES to receive the support and encouragement to complete my journey into the medical feel. column23: Experiencing a reality is often difficult when your exposure is limited to school workshops or pre-health office meetings. column24: My culture will and will always be two-sided. My fathers family came from Virginia and can trace their names far enough back to plantations. My mother’s family is born and bred in Puerto Rico, only moving from the island in the last two generations, my mother and her siblings settled nicely on the mainland, my grandparents drifting to and from without any commitment. I am biracial but raised in my mother’s household. I did not learn about my Blackness from her, but I learned that rice is mandatory with every dinner, that it’s okay that I listen to music when I don’t know what the lyrics mean, that while my mother and her siblings don’t speak Spanish now, they learn it again today with pride instead of shame. I was not raised by my fathers family, but they gave me gospel, fried foods and distant memories of full bellies and tanned shoulders in the summer. I’m not part of either household now, having found my own identity and chosen a different journey but I have found the joys of the city, of being thankful and fostering lifelong relationships with people that don’t share the same blood with me. In the city, I discovered music and cultures not my own, but that I can appreciate and a chain of experiences just as good as any memories. My family and culture are now things I cherish and wish to uphold.
column25: My mother’s family instilled in me a deep respect towards family and helping others in need. On my fathers side there is much more emphasis on respecting the elderly, as we have surviving family members who experienced segregation. Taking the values developed in me from my family, I adapted it to the LGBTQ culture of New York which emphasizes families of choice and impactful/meaningful relationships. Overall, I strive to surround myself with people I admire and respect and develop aspects of myself as I move throughout life.

column22: I want to participate in PrIMES to understand what it takes to be a successful candidate in the medical school application process and what it takes to become a strong physician. As a pre-health undergraduate student, I have received a lot of advice on how to achieve this goal from upperclassmen, faculty, and advisors. However, I think this program would enable me to know what to prioritize concerning my interests.
column23: As a first-generation college student, I believe I would greatly benefit from the personal mentorship and experiences of medical students and physicians. Having the opportunity to receive advice from individuals who have already gone through the process will enable me to get a better idea of what it takes to become a successful medical school applicant. In particular, I am interested in learning about how I can strengthen my extracurricular involvement in medical-related activities, such as volunteering at a small clinic. There aren't any physicians in my family, so hearing from individuals who are pursuing this similar goal would be an amazing opportunity.
column24: My family is the most important part of my life. Most of my family is from the south (i.e., North Carolina and Georgia), but the ones who have remained in New York get together all the time. However, one of my favorite holidays we celebrate together is Christmas. Every year we get together and have a Christmas Eve party with traditional southern cuisine. All of my aunts, uncles, cousins and I exchange gift and wait until midnight to open one gift. My cousins and I often reminisce over this holiday when we get together throughout the year.
column25: My family views respect for our elders as very important. From a young age, I can remember many of my younger cousins and I being scolded for "talking-back" at an inappropriate time. column24: Some observable and concrete elements of my culture would probably be my language. Although, I personally, do not consider this as a huge factor of my culture, I know that many others identify by their language. I personally, enjoy the food of my culture; one of my favorites being pupusas (it's a funny name but they taste incredible). They're made out of corn flour and they can have cheese on the inside or cheese and beans.

column24: I live in a Caribbean household. My parents both come from Jamaica and we speak the traditional language " Patois." Me and my family spend Sundays in church since that is our one time out of the week to worship our god. Some foods I love to eat from my parents country are ackee and saltfish, roast breadfruit, mackerel, jerk chicken, and many more.
column25: In my culture, you are to not have malice or hatred towards anyone and have a forgiving heart. We treat people the way we like to be treated and if there is someone less fortunate in our midst, we help them by giving them the best we can provide. That could look like providing them a warm meal to even opening up our house to someone that needs it while taking into account how well we know them and if there trustworthy to not do anything bad. Friendship is a beautiful thing and is to be cherished and can last a lifetime but you have to recognize that there will be ups and downs. And the downs of the relationship come to strengthen your relationship, not tear it down.

column22: As a first-generation student, not only is the thought of college a new idea but wanting to go to med school is unheard of. This requires figuring out a lot on my own. The people in my life support my dreams but can not guide me or help me access resources due to lack of experience in the field. They also do not understand all the pressures and anxieties I have as a student. I want to participate in prIMES so I can connect with people from a similar background that can relate to my struggles. There is no better way to learn than by having someone who was just in the same position I am now, talking me through it. I want to expand my knowledge by being a member of an entire network of people that are willing to help.  I want to get answers about school that only those who apply and are a medical student can answer. I want people to help guide me through the process of becoming the best medical school applicant I can be instead of only trying to figure it out on my own.
column23: This is my first year at NYU, and I think PrIMES will not only help me create a good foundation but help me create a plan for the future as well.  Having role models and mentorship that can both increase my knowledge and encourage me is important.  It can prevent me from abandoning my goals and be secure in what I know to successfully apply to medical school. PrIMES will also give me more experience so I’m not scrambling trying to figure everything out last minute but instead have the tools to apply. New people can introduce me to new techniques to incorporate into my life like studying strategies that have worked for them. With this kind of individualized instruction, I can start my first year off strong and can set the tone for the rest of my years.
column24: One of my favorite parts of my Colombian culture is Christmas time. Christmas festivities don’t start the 25th or even a few days before but on the 16th. Starting from the 16th to Christmas Eve, Colombians participate in “novenas" which happen each night where everyone from family to neighbors gets together, pray and sing Hispanic Christmas carols. A nativity scene is an iconic part of Christmas. It is also known as a “pesebre” which are insanely elaborate where people go as far as putting real running water or as many lights as possible. Christmas also brings holiday foods like my favorite, Buñuelos.  Nothing compares to the memory of making these fried, cheesy,  doughy treats from scratch on Christmas eve with my grandmother. Other holiday foods include natilla, (a custard) and lechona (pork). Christmas Eve comes with a lot of superstitious activities. One I participated in this year was eating twelve grapes at midnight, each representing a wish as well as good luck for the year. Another is running outside around the block with a suitcase to travel a lot during the year.
column25: There is a lot of pressure put on a child to respect their elders. In the Spanish language, there is tu and usted. Tu is referring to someone else but in an informal setting, usually talking to friends meanwhile usted is more formal. Usted is used for older people. In Colombia, usted is more popular than tu even when talking to close friends. Usted is used as a sign of having more respect for a person, it is also tied to having a higher education because of how formal it is. Elders are seen as all-knowing wise people. When they tell you to do something you don’t question it and if you do, it is a sign of disrespect. Family ties are strong in Latin households which usually house up to 3 generations of family. It is a tradition to take care of older generations and is assumed that the parent will be taken care of in the future and not put in a nursing home instead. Other unspoken rules surrounding social interactions is how there is a lot of negative stigma surrounding talking about both emotions and mental health. Self-reliance when it comes to having problems is valued in the Latin community so it is frowned upon to discuss them. There are negative labels put on people who want to talk through their problems and people are afraid to talk to others who may not understand different cultural issues. It is an unspoken rule to put forth the image of being happy and successful all the time.

column24: Some observable and concrete elements of my culture are how family oriented we are. Having a hispanic heritage, family holds close to our hearts. The food is also very typical and can always be centered around a rice plater, beans and a choice of protein. Music in my household growing up always involved the typical famous colombian salsa.
column25: A couple of typical unspoken rules in my household are always greeting the guest who walks in the house, asking about others day, and offering to help out with household duties. Throughout hispanic culture it is very typical to respect and care for your elders. My family really emphasized to me that our elders take care of us when we're young so it is only right to do the same for them when they get old. Elders in my culture are really cared for and put on a pedestal. Some unspoken rules regarding friendship is support and willingness to provide a helping hand for someone because you never know what they're going through. Eye contact is essentially in communicating because it displays interest in the conversation and attentiveness.
